SIMPLE: prime
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prime
<hw>Prime</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>primus</ets> first, a superl. corresponding to the compar.
<ets>prior</ets> former. See <er>Prior</er>, <pos>a.</pos>,
<er>Foremost</er>, <er>Former</er>, and cf. <er>Prim</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, <er>Primary</er>, <er>Prince</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>First in order of time; original; primeval; primitive;
primary.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Prime</xex> forests.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was not the <qex>prime</qex> cause, but I myself.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense the word is nearly superseded by
<xex>primitive</xex>, except in the phrase <xex>prime
cost</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>First in rank, degree, dignity, authority, or
importance; <as>as, <ex>prime</ex> minister</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Prime</xex> virtues.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>First in excellence; of highest quality; <as>as,
<ex>prime</ex> wheat; a <ex>prime</ex> quality of cloth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Early; blooming; being in the first stage.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His starry helm, unbuckled, showed him <qex>prime</qex>⟦br⟧
In manhood where youth ended.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Lecherous; lustful; lewd.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Marked or distinguished by a mark (⟦prime⟧) called a
<xex>prime mark</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
<note> In this dictionary the same typographic mark is used to indicate
a weak accent in headwords, and minutes of a degree in angle
measurements.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Divisible by no
number except itself or unity; <as>as, 7 is a <ex>prime</ex>
number</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having no common factor; -- used
with <xex>to</xex>; <as>as, 12 is <ex>prime</ex> to 25</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Prime and ultimate ratio</b></col>. <fld>(Math.)</fld>.
<cd>See <er>Ultimate</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Prime conductor</b></col>.
<fld>(Elec.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Conductor</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Prime factor</b></col> <fld>(Arith.)</fld>, <cd>a factor which
is a prime number.</cd> -- <col><b>Prime figure</b></col>
<fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>a figure which can not be divided into any other
figure more simple than itself, as a triangle, a pyramid, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>Prime meridian</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the meridian
from which longitude is reckoned, as the meridian of Greenwich or
Washington.</cd> -- <col><b>Prime minister</b></col>, <cd>the
responsible head of a ministry or executive government; applied
particularly to that of England.</cd> -- <col><b>Prime mover</b></col>.
<fld>(Mech.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A natural agency applied by man to
the production of power. Especially: Muscular force; the weight and
motion of fluids, as water and air; heat obtained by chemical
combination, and applied to produce changes in the volume and pressure
of steam, air, or other fluids; and electricity, obtained by chemical
action, and applied to produce alternation of magnetic force.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An engine, or machine, the object of which is to
receive and modify force and motion as supplied by some natural source,
and apply them to drive other machines; as a water wheel, a
water-pressure engine, a steam engine, a hot-air engine, etc.</cd>
<sd>(c)</sd> Fig.: <cd>The original or the most effective force in any
undertaking or work; <as>as, Clarkson was the <ex>prime</ex> mover in
English antislavery agitation</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Prime
number</b></col> <fld>(Arith.)</fld>, <cd>a number which is exactly
divisible by no number except itself or unity, as 5, 7, 11.</cd> --
<col><b>Prime vertical</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the vertical
circle which passes through the east and west points of the
horizon.</cd> -- <col><b>Prime-vertical dial</b></col>, <cd>a dial in
which the shadow is projected on the plane of the prime vertical.</cd>
-- <col><b>Prime-vertical transit instrument</b></col>, <cd>a transit
instrument the telescope of which revolves in the plane of the prime
vertical, -- used for observing the transit of stars over this
circle.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prime
<hw>Prime</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The first
part; the earliest stage; the beginning or opening, as of the day, the
year, etc.; hence, the dawn; the spring.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the very <qex>prime</qex> of the world.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hope waits upon the flowery <qex>prime</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The spring of life; youth; hence, full health,
strength, or beauty; perfection.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Cut off in their
<xex>prime</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Eustace.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>prime</xex>
of youth.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is first in quantity; the most excellent
portion; the best part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give him always of the <qex>prime</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[F. <ets>prime</ets>, LL. <ets>prima</ets> (sc.
<ets>hora</ets>). See <er>Prime</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>The
morning; specifically <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>, the first canonical hour,
succeeding to lauds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Early and late it rung, at evening and at <qex>prime</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Originally, <xex>prime</xex> denoted the first quarter
of the artificial day, reckoned from 6 <sc>a. m.</sc> to 6 <sc>p.
m.</sc> Afterwards, it denoted the end of the first quarter, that is, 9
<sc>a. m.</sc> Specifically, it denoted the first canonical hour, as
now. Chaucer uses it in all these senses, and also in the sense of def.
1, above.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They sleep till that it was <qex>pryme</qex> large.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Fencing)</fld> <def>The first of the chief
guards.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any number expressing the
combining weight or equivalent of any particular element; -- so called
because these numbers were respectively reduced to their lowest relative
terms on the fixed standard of hydrogen as 1.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>A prime number. See under
<er>Prime</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>An inch, as composed of twelve seconds in the
duodecimal system; -- denoted by [⟦prime⟧]. See 2d <er>Inch</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Prime of the moon</b></col>, <cd>the new moon at its
first appearance.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Prime
<hw>Prime</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Primed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Priming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Prime</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To apply priming to, as a musket
or a cannon; to apply a primer to, as a metallic cartridge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lay the first color, coating, or preparation upon
(a surface), as in painting; <as>as, to <ex>prime</ex> a canvas, a
wall</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To prepare; to make ready; to instruct beforehand;
to post; to coach; <as>as, to <ex>prime</ex> a witness; the boys are
<ex>primed</ex> for mischief.</as></def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To trim or prune, as trees.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>To mark with a prime
mark.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To prime a pump</b></col>, <cd>to charge a pump with
water, in order to put it in working condition.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Prime
<hw>Prime</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be renewed, or as
at first.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night's bashful empress, though she often wane,⟦br⟧
As oft repeats her darkness, <qex>primes</qex> again.</q>
<rj><qau>Quarles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To serve as priming for the charge of a
gun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To work so that foaming occurs from too violent
ebullition, which causes water to become mixed with, and be carried
along with, the steam that is formed; -- said of a steam
boiler.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Primely</ent>⟦br⟧
